First released in 2000 as GB 18030-2000, first revised in 2005; this is the second revision.
GB 18030-2022
Information Expansion "Chinese Character Encoding Set
1 This document specifies the hexadecimal representation of Chinese graphic characters and binary encoding used in information technology.
This document is applicable to the processing, exchange, storage, transmission, display, input and output of Chinese and other text graphic character information.
This document is applicable to technical products with Chinese and other text graphic character information processing and exchange capabilities, including but not limited to software products represented by input methods, optical character recognition (OCR), editing and proofreading, machine translation, speech synthesis, text transcription, intelligent writing, etc., and hardware products represented by computers, communication terminal equipment, e-book readers, learning machines, etc.
2 Normative reference documents
The contents of the following documents constitute essential provisions of this document through normative references.
For the referenced documents with dates, only the version corresponding to the date applies to this document; for the referenced documents without dates, their latest version (including all amendments) applies to this document.
GB/T 2312-1980 "Chinese Character Encoding Set for Information Exchange" Basic Set
GB/I 11383-1989 Information Processing "Eight-bit Code Structure and Encoding Rules for Information Exchange
GB/Work 13000 Universal Multiple Eight-bit Encoding Character Set (UCS)
3 Terms and definitions
The following terms and definitions apply to this document.
3.1 Character
An element in a set of elements used for organizing, controlling or representing data.
3.2 Coded character
Character (3.1) and its encoding.
3.3 Private use area
An area that users of products compliant with this document can define themselves.
3.4 Repertoire
A specified set of characters (3.1) represented by a set of coded characters (3.2).
3.5 Reserved zone
An area reserved for future provisions of this document.
GB 18030-2022
4 Vocabulary
4.1 Overview
The characters included in this document are encoded in single-byte, double-byte or four-byte.
The single-byte part includes all 128 characters from 0x00 to 0x7F in GB/T 11383-1989.
4.3 Double-byte part
The double-byte part includes all graphic characters in GB/T 2312-1980, CJK Unified Ideographs in GB/T 13000 and some graphic characters.
The characters in the double-byte part are according to Appendix A.
The graphics, code positions and functions of ideographic description characters should comply with Appendix B.
Note: GB/T 13000 unifies the encoding of Chinese characters used in China, Japan, South Korea, Vietnam and other countries and regions.
Chinese characters with unique abstract glyphs are assigned separate code positions; Chinese characters with the same abstract glyphs from different sources are assigned shared code positions.
Encoded Chinese characters are called CJK Unified Ideographs, where CJK stands for China, Japan, and Korea.
4.4 Four-byte part
The four-byte part includes 66 CJK Unified Ideographs in GB/T 13000 that are not included in the above-mentioned double-byte characters (9FA6-9FEF, excluding 8 characters from 9FB4 to 9FBB), CJK Unified Ideographs Extension A, CJK Unified Ideographs Extension B, CJK Unified Ideographs Extension C, CJK Unified Ideographs Extension D, CJK Unified Ideographs Extension E, CJK Unified Ideographs Extension F and characters of minority languages that have been encoded in GB/Work 13000.
The characters in the four-byte part are according to Appendix C.
5 Overall structure
In the main text, numbers prefixed with 0x are in hexadecimal, and those without 0x are in decimal.
In the appendix, all encodings are in hexadecimal, and all other numbers are in decimal.
The single-byte part uses the encoding structure of GB/T 11383-1989, using the code positions 0x00~0x7F.
The double-byte part uses two eight-bit binary bit strings to represent a character, with the first byte code positions from 0x81 to 0xFE, and the second byte code positions are 0x40 to 0x7E and 0x80 to 0xFE.
The four-byte part uses the unused 0x30 to 0x39 in GB/Work 11383-1989 as the suffix for expanding the double-byte encoding, with the encoding range from 0x81308130 to 0xFE39FE39.
The encoding range of the first byte of the four-byte character is 0x81 to 0xFE; the second byte is 0x30 to 0x39; the third byte is 0x81 to 0xFE; the fourth byte is 0x30 to 0x39. That is: 0x81308130 to 0x81308139; 0x81308230 to 0x81308239 0x8130FEFE30 to 0x8130FE39; 0x81318130 to 0x81318139; 0x81318230 to 0x81318239 0xFE39FE30 to 0xFE39FE39.
The overall structure and code position allocation are shown in Figure 1 and Table 1.
6 Character arrangement order
6.1 Single-byte part character arrangement order
The characters in the single-byte part are arranged in the order of the corresponding characters in GB/I 11383-1989.
6.2 Double-byte part character arrangement order
The character arrangement order of the double-byte part should comply with Appendix A.
6.3 Four-byte part character arrangement order
From 0x81308130 to 0x8439FE39, a total of 50400 code positions, corresponding to all characters in the GB/T 13000 basic multilingual plane not included in the double-byte part, are arranged in the order of the corresponding characters in the GB/T 13000 basic multilingual plane.
From 0x90308130 to 0xE339FE39, a total of 1058400 code positions are used to correspond to the 16 auxiliary planes of GB/T 13000, and the character arrangement order is completely arranged in the order of the corresponding code positions of the 16 auxiliary planes of GB/I 13000.
The character arrangement order of the four-byte part should comply with Appendix C.
