Executive Summary
The Impact of COVID-19 on the Drug Market
Its impact may be similar to the 2008 economic crisis
The global COVID-19 pandemic has plunged the world into an unprecedented crisis.
In many countries, this disease has overwhelmed healthcare services, bringing them to the brink of collapse, and the restrictive measures implemented by governments have caused serious disruption in the global economy.
The impact of this pandemic on the drug market is still unclear and difficult to predict, but it could be profound.
Some producers may be forced to find new ways to manufacture drugs, as restrictions on movement also limit the acquisition of precursors and basic chemicals.
Traffickers, unable to cross borders due to travel restrictions, may have to find new routes and methods.
The patterns of drug use and supply may change, and the government's ability to respond may be hindered.
The changes brought about by COVID-19 are unprecedented, but some lessons can still be learned from past crises.
After the 2008 economic crisis, some drug users began to look for cheaper synthetic substances, and the pattern of use shifted towards injecting drugs.
At the same time, governments around the world cut budgets related to drugs.
If governments respond to the current economic recession in the same way, interventions to prevent drug use and related risky behaviors, as well as drug treatment services, may take a heavy hit.
In addition, the priority of interception operations and international cooperation may decrease, making it easier for traffickers to operate.
Some countries have a large amount of drugs smuggled through commercial flights, and these countries are expected to be most directly affected by drug trafficking activities.
Couriers carry synthetic drugs such as methamphetamine in carry-on backpacks or hidden in personal luggage, sometimes in large quantities. Due to restrictions on air passenger transport almost everywhere, activities supplying drugs through commercial air travel may be completely interrupted.
Although the international postal supply chain has also been disrupted, trafficking activities using the dark web and cargo mail may increase.
In the long run, economic recession and related lockdown measures may disrupt the drug market.
Due to rising unemployment rates and lack of opportunities, the poor and vulnerable are more likely to use drugs in harmful ways, develop drug-related diseases, and turn to illegal activities related to drugs - whether production or transportation.
Drug trafficking organizations may take advantage of this situation, provide services to vulnerable populations, and recruit new members to strengthen their ranks.
As government response capabilities decrease, these changes may quickly take root and become the new reality for many communities.
Expansion and Complexity
Market Growth
Population growth patterns partly explain market expansion
Drug use is increasing worldwide, both in absolute numbers and as a proportion of the world's population.
In 2009, it was estimated that there were 210 million drug users, accounting for 4.8% of the global population aged 15-64, while in 2018, it was estimated that there were 269 million drug users, accounting for 5.3% of this population.
Over the past twenty years, the growth rate of drug use in developing countries has far outpaced that in developed countries.
This to some extent reflects the difference in overall population growth during this period, with developed countries at 7% and developing countries at 28%, but also reflects the faster growth of the young population in developing countries.
Teenagers and young adults make up the largest proportion of drug users.
Between 2000 and 2018, the population in this age group in developing countries grew by 16%, while in developed countries it decreased by 10%.
Urbanization is a driving factor in the current and future drug market
Whether in developed or developing countries, drug use is more prevalent in urban areas than in rural areas.
Part of the reason for the overall increase in drug use is the large-scale movement of people from rural to urban areas - currently more than half of the world's population lives in urban areas, compared to 34% in 1960.
Urbanization may be a key factor in the future dynamics of the drug market, especially in developing countries where the trend towards urbanization is more pronounced.
Increased wealth is associated with increased drug use, but the greatest burden of disease is borne by the poorest. Globally, drug use is more common in developed countries than in developing countries.
Drugs like cocaine are more firmly linked to wealthier regions of the world.
Similarly, within countries, drug prevalence rates are higher among the affluent social classes.
However, those with lower socioeconomic status have a higher rate of transition to drug-related diseases.
Data from a few countries suggest that harmful drug use patterns and diseases are associated with low income.
These patterns seem less common in wealthier social classes.
The economic constraints caused by the global COVID-19 crisis are likely to exacerbate the risks for the most vulnerable groups, including drug users.
For example, changes in the labor market, such as rising unemployment rates, have always been associated with an increase in drug use, and this pandemic has already forced tens of millions of people worldwide to lose their jobs.
COVID-19 may lead to further expansion of the drug market. The pandemic may lead to more farmers increasing or engaging in illegal crop cultivation, either because of reduced control by national authorities or because more people may have to take risks and engage in illegal activities in the face of economic crisis.
The COVID-19 related restrictions have led to a reduction in air and land transport, and sea trafficking may have increased as a result, with lower interception risks at sea and larger quantities than air or land smuggling.
There have been recent reports of cocaine shipments being sent directly from South America to Europe by sea.
Complexity Enhanced
The occurrence of non-internationally controlled substances is stable, but new types of potentially harmful opiates are increasing, making the drug market increasingly complex.
In addition to plant substances such as cannabis, cocaine, and heroin, hundreds of synthetic drugs have been added, many of which are not under international control. Non-medical use of drugs is also rapidly increasing.
Member countries have about 500 new active substances on their domestic markets each year.
Most of them are currently stimulants, followed by synthetic cannabinoid receptor agonists and a small amount of opiates.
Although the total number of new psychoactive substances has stabilized, the proportion has changed.
In the total number of new psychoactive substances identified in 2014, new psychoactive opiates accounted for only 2%, but by 2018, this number had risen to 9%.
Many of the new psychoactive opiates are fentanyl analogs, whose efficacy and harm have been proven, causing overdose deaths in North America and other regions, but to a lesser extent.
In North America, some fentanyl is used as an adulterant for heroin and other drugs (including cocaine and methamphetamine), and some is used to manufacture counterfeit medicinal opiates.
Some evidence suggests that there is also a phenomenon of injecting new psychoactive substance stimulants in Europe: a study of discarded syringe residues in six European cities found that many syringes were contaminated with new psychoactive substances that produce stimulant effects.
2 The use of new psychoactive substances may gradually become entrenched in vulnerable groups
A single type of new psychoactive substance has almost never formed a large market.
But evidence from Europe suggests that synthetic cannabinoids are a serious problem among socially marginalized groups such as the homeless and prison inmates.
22 countries have reported the use of new psychoactive substances in prisons, with most countries identifying synthetic cannabinoids as the main challenge.
Control of precursor chemicals forces drug manufacturers to innovate. Many chemicals used as precursors to synthesize amphetamines, methamphetamines, and "ecstasy" have been placed under international control.
Drug traffickers and manufacturers are always looking for alternatives, not only substances with looser controls, but also chemicals specifically designed to evade control, the so-called "specially designed precursors".
Restrictive measures aimed at preventing the spread of COVID-19 are likely to further squeeze drug manufacturers who rely on precursor chemicals.
Evidence from Mexico suggests that this has become a reality: according to reports, in March 2020, a shortage of methamphetamine precursors imported from East Asia prompted a rise in methamphetamine prices in Mexico and the United States.
The market is changing rapidly
Synthetic drugs replace opiates in Central Asia and the Russian Federation
The opiate market in Central Asia and the Russian Federation seems to have changed from 2008 to 2018.
The number of opiates intercepted by the Russian Federation authorities has dropped by about 80%, while the number of people receiving treatment for opiate use has significantly decreased.
But the stimulant market seems to be thriving.
There is evidence that methamphetamine and various cathinones, including methoxymethcathinone and a-pyrrolidinopentiophenone, are now ubiquitous in the Russian drug market.
Russian authorities report that the number of secret processing points for the production of various illegal drugs has surged, more than doubling in two years, increasing to 152 processing points in 2018.
Methamphetamine market growth in Afghanistan and Iraq
As early as 2012, surveys of hospital, prison, and other institutional staff had already revealed the importance of methamphetamine in Iraq.
Crystalline methamphetamine has become another major drug of concern, in addition to "phenethylamine" and tramadol.
A 2015 study further confirmed these findings, with drug users stating that cannabis was harder to obtain than "phenethylamine" or methamphetamine.
Recently, Iraqi authorities have discovered multiple methamphetamine processing points, and the Bureau of Narcotics has expressed concern about the large imports of pseudoephedrine preparations - methamphetamine processing points use these preparations as precursors.
In Afghanistan, methamphetamine production seems to have started in 2014.
Since then, the amount of methamphetamine seized has been steadily increasing.
But the amount seized in the first half of 2019 - 657 kilograms - was a sharp increase compared to the previous year.
Large seizures of methamphetamine believed to originate from Afghanistan in other countries also indicate that the country's production is rapidly increasing.
Policy Changes and Trends
Most jurisdictions where non-medical use of cannabis is legalized have seen an increase in cannabis use.
Canada, Uruguay, and 11 jurisdictions in the United States allow the production of cannabis products for non-medical use.
In most of these jurisdictions, cannabis use has increased since legalization, although the same trend has been observed in other jurisdictions where non-medical use of cannabis has not been legalized.
In Colorado and Washington, the first two states in the United States to pass legislation, adult non-medical use of cannabis has increased, especially in the past month and daily or almost daily use, which has exceeded the national average since 2012.
All indicators show that since 2011, cannabis use in Uruguay has increased, with last month's use almost doubling.
This suggests that the main reason for the increase is frequent and regular use of cannabis.
Short-term data from Canada also shows that as the legal market expanded from 2018 to 2019, usage also increased.
However, in 2019, 40% of cannabis users still obtained some products from illegal sources.
Is the reason behind the global plunge in cannabis seizures the legalization of cannabis?
In 2018, global cannabis seizures fell to their lowest level in 20 years, due to a 84% decrease in North America over the past 10 years.
In contrast, seizures in other parts of the world during the same period almost doubled. The pattern of seizures suggests that policies aimed at liberalizing the cannabis market played a key role in the decline.
The regulation of new psychoactive substances seems to have a deterrent effect, but it is still difficult to assess the effectiveness of domestic regulation of new psychoactive substances.
Countries with different regulatory systems for new psychoactive substances show different prevalence rates of use.
In some other countries, the use of new psychoactive substances has decreased after domestic legislation.
Vulnerable groups face harm from both legal and illegal drug markets. Opioids for pain management and palliative care are mainly provided in high-income countries, with uneven distribution across regions.
In 2018, over 90% of all medically available opioids were in high-income countries.
About 50% in North America, 40% in Europe, and 2% in Oceania.
The population of these countries accounts for about 12% of the global population.
It is estimated that the population of low- and middle-income countries accounts for 88% of the global population, but consumes less than 10% of medically available opioids.
Barriers to accessing opioids for medical use are related to many factors, including legislation, culture, health systems, and prescribing practices.
Poorer people are at greater risk of drug addiction. In 2018, about 35.6 million people had drug addiction.
Poverty, limited education, and social marginalization may increase the risk of drug addiction and exacerbate its consequences. This has been confirmed by research in high-income countries, where individuals' adverse socioeconomic trajectories - not just their status at a given point in time - are associated with the risk of drug addiction.
Drug addiction can also exacerbate socioeconomic disadvantages, further increasing the risk of unemployment, poverty, and homelessness, thereby fueling a vicious cycle of disadvantage. These outcomes may also be related to stigmatizing attitudes and consequences within the criminal justice system.
Women, ethnic minorities and immigrants, diverse sexual orientation groups, people displaced by armed conflict or disaster, and people in rural environments may also be disproportionately affected by drug addiction, or encounter problems in accessing treatment services.
According to the Disability Adjusted Life Years (DALY) indicator, which estimates the loss of healthy life years due to disability and premature death, the harmful effects of drug use on a wider social impact have increased over the past 10 years.
From 2007 to 2018, the global Disability Adjusted Life Years attributed to drug use increased by 17%.
The increase in Disability Adjusted Life Years associated with liver cancer caused by untreated hepatitis C, which is common among injecting drug users, was particularly high - up to 40%.
The relationship between drugs and violence is complex and it is difficult to determine all the causal relationships between the use of psychoactive substances and violence.
Limited global data suggests that intoxication may be an important factor in homicide.
However, in violent incidents, alcohol seems to play a bigger role than drugs.
Although drug use can lead to crime, in some cases, this link can be partly attributed to various mediating factors, such as socioeconomic disadvantage and other types of adversity caused by individual risk, family environment, and peer influence.
The link between drug trafficking and violence is multifaceted.
If there is already a stable criminal structure, large-scale organized criminal activities, including international drug trafficking, can potentially be carried out without violence.
In the short term, the presence and degree of violence depend less on the amount of trafficking than on certain changes that destabilize the balance of power among organized crime groups, such as changes in the size of the illegal market, the death or imprisonment of notorious criminals, and law enforcement measures that weaken one group relative to another.
Latest Trends
Marijuana is the most commonly used substance, with opioids posing the greatest harm.
It is estimated that in 2018, 192 million people used marijuana, making it the most widely used drug globally.
In contrast, 58 million people used opioids in 2018.
However, the associated harms of opioid drugs are often overlooked due to fewer users.
Of the estimated 167,000 drug-related deaths in 2017, 66% were caused by these substances, and of the 21 million years of life lost due to disability or premature death believed to be caused by drug use, 50% were caused by these substances.
Non-medical use of synthetic opioids has exacerbated the public health crisis.
In West Africa, Central Africa, and North Africa, the opioid crisis is exacerbated by Tramadol; in North America, it is Fentanyl. These two regions have little in common in terms of economy, demographic data, or general drug use patterns, but both are struggling to combat the opioid crisis fueled by easily accessible and low-cost substances.
In North America, the use of synthetic opioids like fentanyl has led to an increase in opioid overdose deaths over the past 20 years.
In 2018, two-thirds of the 67,367 overdose deaths registered in the United States involved fentanyl.
Canada has also reported similar results, albeit with lower numbers.
Part of the reason for fentanyl-related overdose deaths is the unpredictable potency of fentanyl on the illegal drug market.
In West Africa, Central Africa, and North Africa, the market for non-medical use of Tramadol has seen significant growth.
In this region, there are an increasing number of patients with Tramadol use disorders receiving treatment.
In 2017, the global seizure of Tramadol significantly increased, reaching a peak of over 125 tons.
However, in 2018, after India passed a new law to regulate Tramadol, the global seizure volume dropped to 32 tons.
The crises in these two places are driven by simple manufacturing and low production costs, as well as a lack of international regulation for Tramadol and many fentanyl-like substances or their precursors.
The crises in these two places are exacerbated by the fact that these substances are supplied in both the legal and illegal markets, making it even more difficult to detect and prevent their misuse.
Stimulant use is on the rise
The stimulant field is dominated by cocaine and methamphetamine, both of which are seeing increased use in their main markets.
In 2018, about 19 million people used cocaine, as it is quite popular in North America and Western Europe.
In the same year, about 27 million people used amphetamines, with methamphetamine being the most commonly used amphetamine stimulant in Southeast Asia and North America.
According to most indicators available, the use of methamphetamine in these two regions has been expanding over the past 20 years.
In some markets, cocaine and methamphetamine can coexist, sometimes substituting for each other, so that when the use of one drug increases, the use of the other decreases, and sometimes both increase and decrease to meet the same market demand.
COVID-19 increases the risk for injecting drug users
It is estimated that in 2018, about 11.3 million people injected drugs, and about 10% of global HIV infections were caused by injecting drugs.
Over 1 million injecting drug users are infected with HIV, and 5.5 million have hepatitis C.
In 2017, about 585,000 people died from drug use, half of whom died from liver disease caused by hepatitis C, and most injecting drug users with hepatitis C have not yet been treated.
The shortage of opioids caused by COVID-19 restrictions may lead users to substitute with more readily available substances such as alcohol or benzodiazepines, or to mix opioids with synthetic drugs.
As some users switch to injecting or inject more frequently, more harmful methods of use may emerge.
