(Deutsche Welle Chinese) Several days have passed since the earthquake in parts of Turkey and Syria, and the hope of finding survivors is fading. However, the rescue of a family of five on Saturday brought great relief to the rescuers.
According to the Associated Press, in the heavily affected town of Nurdai in Gaziantep province, this family of five was successfully rescued after being trapped under the rubble for more than five days.
Rescuers first pulled the mother and daughter from the rubble, then found the father, who insisted on rescuing his son and another daughter first.
When they were all rescued, cheers erupted from the crowd.
In the southern Turkish city of Kahramanmaras, a 16-year-old boy and a 70-year-old woman were also successfully rescued in harsh cold weather conditions.
"What day is it today?
" - the boy who had been trapped under the rubble for 129 hours asked the rescuer who brought him back to the surface.
A man in Kahramanmaras holding his newly rescued cat.
Miraculous successful rescue cases brought a glimmer of hope to the originally hopeless rescue work, but at the same time, the number of casualties is also rising.
According to official statistics, Monday's earthquake has caused more than 20,000 deaths in Turkey, and the death toll in neighboring Syria is estimated to be over 3,500.
Although experts say that people can survive for more than a week after being trapped in the rubble, the hope of finding more survivors is becoming increasingly slim.
Rescuers are still using thermal imaging devices to search for signs of life under the rubble.
At the same time, the focus of the rescue work has begun to shift towards helping those survivors who are in urgent need of assistance.
UN official: The region's "once-in-a-century" disaster
Martin Griffiths, the UN Under-Secretary-General for Humanitarian Affairs and Emergency Relief Coordinator, said at a press conference in Turkey that the earthquake was the worst disaster in the region in a century.
He also praised Turkey's response to the disaster as "extraordinary".
He also told Reuters reporters that he hoped to provide aid to areas controlled by the Syrian government and the opposition, but also said that the relevant matters were "not clear".
The United Nations has pledged an additional $25 million in relief donations to the earthquake-stricken people in Syria.
Earlier this week, the United Nations announced a donation of $25 million for disaster relief in Turkey and Syria.
The most destructive earthquakes in the world in the last 60 years
Chile earthquake (1960)
At 3:11 p.m. local time on May 22, 1960, the largest earthquake ever recorded in human history occurred in Valdivia, Chile, with a moment magnitude of 9.5.
Within just ten minutes, the entire city of Valdivia was reduced to rubble.
The massive tsunami triggered by the earthquake hit the Chilean coastline, causing waves up to 25 meters high.
The tsunami affected distant Japan and the Philippines.
The number of casualties and economic losses caused by such a wide-ranging disaster are unknown.
The most destructive earthquakes in the world in the last 60 years
Alaska earthquake (1964)
March 27, 1964, was a Friday and also Good Friday.
On this day, the largest earthquake in North American history occurred in Alaska, with a moment magnitude of 9.2.
Until 2006, the Alaska earthquake was still the third largest earthquake on record.
When the earthquake occurred, a fault between the Pacific Plate and the North American Plate ruptured near Prince William Sound and College Fjord.
In most areas, the earthquake lasted for 3 to 5 minutes.
The displacement of the seabed triggered a huge tsunami, with a height of 67 meters.
Because it was a holiday, schools and many businesses were closed.
The earthquake eventually resulted in 139 deaths.
Nine people died directly from the earthquake, and the other 130 died from the tsunami triggered by the earthquake.
The most destructive earthquakes in the world in the last 60 years
Tangshan earthquake (1976)
On July 28, 1976, two strong earthquakes above magnitude 7 occurred in Tangshan City and Fengnan County, Hebei Province, China, within 16 hours.
The epicenter was 23 kilometers from the surface.
The entire city of Tangshan was leveled in an instant, with transportation, communication, water supply, and electricity cut off.
There was a strong tremor in Beijing, 140 kilometers away.
According to official statistics, the earthquake caused 242,769 deaths and 164,851 serious injuries in all affected areas, including Beijing and Tianjin.
The Tangshan earthquake was the second deadliest earthquake on record in China, second only to the Jiajing earthquake in 1556.
However, some overseas scientists estimate that the earthquake may have caused at least 650,000 deaths.
The most destructive earthquakes in the world in the last 60 years
Indian Ocean earthquake (2004)
On December 26, 2004, an earthquake occurred 160 kilometers off the west coast of Aceh Province, Sumatra, Indonesia, with a depth of 30 kilometers and a moment magnitude of 9.1 to 9.3.
The earthquake triggered a huge tsunami with wave heights of 15 to 30 meters.
A total of 14 countries along the Pacific coast were affected, with the most severely affected areas including Aceh Province in Indonesia, Hua Hin and Phuket resort areas in Thailand, Sri Lanka, and Tamil Nadu in India.
At the time, it was the peak tourist season for Christmas, and the affected areas were crowded with a large number of tourists and local residents, resulting in many tourists enjoying their holidays on the beach and local people working by the sea being swept into the sea by the tsunami, making many people missing from this earthquake.
It is estimated that the number of deaths and missing persons is at least 300,000.
The most destructive earthquakes in the world in the last 60 years
Wenchuan earthquake (2008)
On May 12, 2008, a major earthquake occurred in Wenchuan, Sichuan Province, China.
According to data from the China Earthquake Administration, the surface wave magnitude of this earthquake reached 8.2, the moment magnitude reached 8.3, and the affected area exceeded 100,000 square kilometers.
As of September 25, 2008, the earthquake had caused 69,227 deaths, 17,923 missing, 374,643 injuries of varying degrees, 19.93 million people lost their homes, and the total affected population reached 46.256 million.
It was the most destructive earthquake since the founding of the People's Republic of China and the deadliest since the Tangshan earthquake.
In March 2009, the State Council of China declared May 12 as the National Disaster Prevention and Reduction Day each year to strengthen education for the public and attention to disaster prevention and reduction work.
Subsequently, many local governments and primary and secondary schools in China held earthquake drills on this day every year.
Primary and secondary schools also began to pay attention to the popularization of "disaster prevention and reduction" education.
The most destructive earthquakes in the world in the last 60 years
Haiti earthquake (2010)
On January 12, 2010, a magnitude 7.0 earthquake struck the Caribbean island nation of Haiti.
The epicenter was located about 25 kilometers southwest of the capital, Port-au-Prince, and the focus was about 13 kilometers below the surface.
The International Red Cross estimates that about 3 million people were affected by the earthquake.
The Haitian government announced that the confirmed death toll exceeded 200,000.
In some areas of Haiti, up to 90% of the houses were destroyed in the earthquake.
Despite a lot of aid and support from the international community, this overpopulated and corruptly impoverished country has never recovered from this disaster.
The most destructive earthquakes in the world in the last 60 years
Tohoku earthquake in Japan (2011)
On March 11, 2011, a large thrust earthquake with a moment magnitude of 9.0 occurred off the coast of the Tohoku region of Japan.
The epicenter was located in the Pacific Ocean east of Sendai, the capital of Miyagi Prefecture, with a focal depth of 24 kilometers, and it triggered a huge tsunami with a maximum run-up height of 40.1 meters.
This earthquake was the first earthquake in Japan with a magnitude over 9 on record.
About 22,000 people died in the disaster, and about 400,000 buildings were completely destroyed or collapsed.
The Fukushima Daiichi nuclear power plant was affected by the earthquake and tsunami and a leakage accident occurred.
This accident was classified as the most serious level 7 in the International Nuclear Event Scale (INES).
The Fukushima nuclear accident resulted in trace amounts of radioactive substances being measured worldwide, including iodine-131 and cesium-137 (with a half-life of 30 years).
A large amount of radioactive isotopes were released into the Pacific Ocean due to this nuclear accident.
According to United Nations statistics, in the disaster areas of Turkey and Syria, at least 870,000 people are currently in urgent need of food.
In Syria alone, as many as 5.3 million people have lost their homes due to the earthquake.
The World Food Programme (WFP) is calling for a donation of 77 million US dollars to provide food for the displaced people in Turkey and Syria due to the earthquake.
The current temperature in the disaster area is below zero, and many victims have no place to live.
The Turkish government has distributed a large number of hot meals, tents, and blankets, but these supplies are still difficult to deliver to many people who urgently need help.
In Syria, which has been mired in civil war for as long as 12 years, the earthquake has added to the suffering of the people.
Within four days after the earthquake, the World Food Programme has provided food relief to 115,000 people in Turkey and Syria.
The World Health Organization (WHO) has sent 72 tons of medical supplies for trauma treatment and emergency surgery.
