Singapore's tourism industry recovers strongly, with inbound tourists increasing 19 times compared to 2021
(Comprehensive news on the 11th) The Singapore Tourism Board recently announced that it is expected that the number of international tourists visiting Singapore in 2023 will reach 12 to 14 million, bringing about 18 to 21 billion Singapore dollars in tourism revenue; the number of tourists and tourism revenue will recover to about 67% to 75% of the level before the COVID-19 outbreak in 2019; there is a high possibility of a full recovery of the tourism industry in 2024.
In 2022, Singapore's tourism market gradually restarted and recovered.
The latest statistics released by the Singapore Tourism Board show that the number of inbound tourists in 2022 increased 19 times from 330,600 in 2021 to 6.3 million, surpassing the earlier estimate of 4 to 6 million by the Tourism Board, and tourists have recovered to 33% of the level before the pandemic.
From January to September 2022, Singapore's tourism revenue totaled 8.96 billion Singapore dollars, and it is expected that the total tourism revenue for 2022 will reach 13.8 to 14.3 billion Singapore dollars, an increase of 6 to 7 times from 1.89 billion Singapore dollars in 2021, and has recovered to about 50% to 52% of the level before the COVID-19 outbreak in 2019.
The Singapore government has taken multiple measures to accelerate the recovery of the tourism industry.
In April 2022, the government announced a grant of nearly 500 million Singapore dollars to stimulate the recovery of the tourism industry.
The Tourism Board recently announced that it plans to allocate 110 million Singapore dollars from this budget over the next two years to launch more business and leisure activities to attract tourists back.
In order to make health and wellness one of the highlights of Singapore's tourism, the Singapore Tourism Board launched a call for proposals on November 23, 2022, planning to develop a health and wellness attraction on the southern coast of Singapore.
Wang Lingli, Executive Director of Sports and Wellness Tourism at the Singapore Tourism Board, said that in recent years, more and more tourists have put physical health at the top of their considerations.
Developing a health and wellness attraction in the Marina South area, which has the Gardens by the Bay and the Marina Barrage, is expected to contribute to Singapore's tourism industry and economy, allowing tourists to spend and stay longer in Singapore.
Chen Jianlong, Director of the Singapore Tourism Board, said that in the next few years, health and wellness will become an important part of Singapore's tourism products.
The COVID-19 pandemic has raised public awareness and demand for physical and mental health.
For this reason, the Tourism Board has been promoting health and wellness projects to the local public and international tourists for the past two years.
In June 2022, the Singapore Tourism Board held the first Health and Wellness Festival, providing the public with more than 130 various health activities and experiences.
Singapore will continue to provide new travel experiences for tourists.
In addition to the newly opened Singapore Children's Museum, Avatar World at Gardens by the Bay, Central Beach Market in Sentosa, the new "Exploring New Territories" exhibition hall at the ArtScience Museum, and the newly built open-air theater at the Night Safari, the Tourism Board will support the development and renewal of projects such as the Bird Park at Wildlife Reserves Singapore, making Singapore an attractive international travel destination.
According to the plan, Singapore will establish industry standards for the sustainable development of the meetings, incentives, conferences and exhibitions (MICE) industry within 2023, and focus on improving waste management and carbon emissions, further optimizing the tourism environment.
The recovery of Singapore's tourism industry has accelerated the recovery of the aviation industry.
Data shows that as of December 18, 2022, passenger traffic at Changi Airport has strongly recovered, with as many as 150,000 passengers received daily, about 1 million per week, which is about 75% of the level before the COVID-19 outbreak, and the number of aviation industry employees on duty has also recovered to about 90% of the level before the pandemic.
Data shows that from January to October 2022, Singapore has received 23.6 million tourists, which is 42% of the level before the COVID-19 outbreak, and 170,000 flights have taken off and landed, which is 53% of the level before the pandemic.
The rapid recovery of the tourism industry has also driven the recovery of industries such as accommodation, transportation, catering, and shopping.
The Singapore government and the tourism industry have high hopes for the Chinese market.
Ke Shudan, Assistant Director of the International Department of the Singapore Tourism Board, said that a survey by a Chinese travel platform shows that Singapore's safety index ranks among the top three in the world, which is also one of the reasons why Singapore is popular with Chinese tourists.
Before the COVID-19 outbreak, about 3.6 million Chinese people traveled to Singapore for vacations each year.
With China relaxing its border policy, it is expected that the number of Chinese tourists this year can recover to 30% to 60% of the level in 2019.
Ke Shudan pointed out that next, the Tourism Board will closely monitor signals from China for further relaxation of outbound travel policies to respond to changes in tourist demand.
In addition to strengthening partnerships with Chinese online travel platforms and travel agencies such as Ctrip, the Singapore Tourism Board will prepare to receive Chinese tourists in response to new trends in outbound travel from China.
Looking forward to the tourism market in 2023, the Singapore Tourism Board is confident that as long as there is no significant economic downturn affecting public income, and no new large-scale fatal epidemic outbreaks, the recovery of the tourism industry will be faster than expected.
