The last Communist Prime Minister of East Germany passed away today.
The successors of the East German Communist Party reported in a statement, "Last night, Hans Modrow left us at the age of 95.
Thus, our party has lost an important leader.
"
On November 13, 1989, four days after the Berlin Wall, which had separated East and West Berlin for 28 years, was opened, Modrow stated that he would help transform East Germany into a democratic country.
At that time, due to protesters across East Germany demanding democracy and freedom, the Communist Party leaders were forced to step down.
After Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in the Soviet Union, he called for reforms in Eastern Europe under Soviet leadership.
In March 1990, Modrow announced the first and only free election of the German Democratic Republic (GDR).
The election results led to him no longer serving as Prime Minister.
Although Modrow carried out reforms, opponents accused him of trying to delay the political changes and unification that occurred in October 1990.
He was also criticized for trying to reshape rather than abolish the secret police.
In 1993, Modrow was found guilty of election fraud in the municipal elections of May 1989, but was not imprisoned.
Some say these charges were politically motivated.
From 1990 to 1994, Modrow continued to serve in the German Parliament and was a member of the European Parliament from 1999 to 2004.
Modrow saw himself as a reformer and wanted to change the Communist Party from within.
In 1999, he told Reuters that he did not want the old East Germany to return, but said that East Germany's achievements should be recognized.
Modrow was born in 1928 in the small German town of Jasenitz (now Jasienica in Poland) and received training as a mechanic.
During World War II, he served as a youth fire brigade leader and became a member of the Nazi militia organization Volkssturm, which drafted men aged 16 to 60 for the final struggle of the war, as the conflict was nearing its end.
At the age of 17, Modrow was captured by the Soviet army and taken to the Soviet Union as a prisoner of war, where he attended anti-fascist courses and became a staunch Communist.
In 1949, the year East Germany was established, he returned home to find a job as a mechanic, continued to study social sciences and economics, and earned a doctorate.
Modrow was a staff member of the Free German Youth Movement, which almost all young people in East Germany joined, and he rose to become the chairman of the Dresden regional party through the ruling Socialist Unity Party (SED) from 1973 to 1989.
He also served in the East German parliament for over 30 years.
In 1990, Modrow became the de facto leader of East Germany, holding the highest state office.
